abstract: Mr. Biden has gone on the offensive, taking aim at two rivals ahead of him in the Iowa results, Pete Buttigieg and Bernie Sanders, while Ms. Warren continues to stress unity.
snippet: Mr. Biden has gone on the offensive, taking aim at two rivals ahead of him in the Iowa results, Pete Buttigieg and Bernie Sanders, while Ms. Warren continues to stress unity.
lead_paragraph: MANCHESTER, N.H. — Joseph R. Biden Jr. and Senator Elizabeth Warren each suffered a damaging setback in Iowa that could make it harder for them to recover next week in New Hampshire — and not just because they were running well behind the leading candidates as Democrats awaited a final count.

abstract: Another gay judge said Judge Batts “literally broke down the closet door and allowed the rest of us to walk through it.”
snippet: Another gay judge said Judge Batts “literally broke down the closet door and allowed the rest of us to walk through it.”
lead_paragraph: Deborah A. Batts, the first openly gay judge to sit on the federal bench, who presided over prominent cases involving political corruption, terrorism and the Central Park Five civil case, died on Monday at her home in Manhattan. She was 72.

abstract: About 37 million Americans tuned in on Tuesday, the smallest audience of President Trump’s tenure.
snippet: About 37 million Americans tuned in on Tuesday, the smallest audience of President Trump’s tenure.
lead_paragraph: President Trump put a “Celebrity Apprentice” spin on his State of the Union address on Tuesday, seeding the 78-minute broadcast with surprise reveals and viral moments: a tear-stained reunion of a military family, a snubbed handshake and an impromptu bestowing of the Presidential Medal of Freedom to a guest star, the radio host Rush Limbaugh.

abstract: The Senate's vote to acquit President Donald Trump not only ended the impeachment saga Wednesday, it shut off the source of hours of programming for television news networks.

abstract: The growing extremism of the debate alienates many people on the left and right.
snippet: The growing extremism of the debate alienates many people on the left and right.
lead_paragraph: Where will abortion opponents stand in 2020? President Trump recently made his bid for their votes, becoming the first president to speak in person at the annual March for Life in Washington, an event held since 1974. Two days later, a Democratic presidential hopeful, Pete Buttigieg, told a woman who called herself a “proud pro-life Democrat” that he would not support more moderate abortion language in the Democratic National Committee platform — basically suggesting that, on this issue, she will not find affirmation or support from her party.
